  <reviews>
    <item index="0">
      <text>The plotting is contrived, the supporting characters two-dimensional, and the ending slides from predictable to absurd to maudlin.</text>
      <source>Time Out</source>
      <image>rottentomatoes://image.review.rotten</image>
      <link>http://www.timeout.com/film/reviews/85392/redbelt.html</link>
      <author>Ben Walters</author>
    </item>
    <item index="1">
      <text>David Mamet must have gotten roundhouse kicked in the head to think there was a story worth telling in his latest macho faceoff.</text>
      <source>I.E. Weekly</source>
      <image>rottentomatoes://image.review.rotten</image>
      <link>http://www.ieweekly.com/cms/story/detail/redbelt/1225/</link>
      <author>Amy Nicholson</author>
    </item>
    <item index="2">
      <text>What is memorable is the film's portrait of a man of honor in a sleazy world, possibly a metaphor for the struggle of the artist to stay honorable in a world of backbiting, betrayal and hunger for easy money.</text>
      <source>Washington Post</source>
      <image>rottentomatoes://image.review.fresh</image>
      <link>http://www.washingtonpost.com/ac2/wp-dyn?node=cityguide/profile&amp;id=1141812&amp;categories=Movies&amp;nm=1</link>
      <author>Stephen Hunter</author>
    </item>
    <item index="3">
      <text>The glue that holds it together is Ejiofor's muscular performance as a man whose principles may be about to feel the brass knuckles of reality.</text>
      <source>Toronto Star</source>
      <image>rottentomatoes://image.review.fresh</image>
      <link>http://www.thestar.com/entertainment/article/423141</link>
      <author>Peter Howell</author>
    </item>
    <item index="4">
      <text>David Mamet's take on the trendy new world of mixed martial arts is a gem not quite like anything I've seen before Ã¢" a smart, absorbing, anti-Hollywood, hypermacho look at what it is to be a true martial artist and a man.</text>
      <source>Seattle Times</source>
      <image>rottentomatoes://image.review.fresh</image>
      <link>http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/movies/2004401341_redbelt090.html</link>
      <author>Mark Rahner</author>
    </item>
    <item index="5">
      <text>Mamet's love for the sport comes through in every frame.</text>
      <source>San Francisco Chronicle</source>
      <image>rottentomatoes://image.review.fresh</image>
      <link>http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?file=/c/a/2008/05/09/DDL410IH84.DTL</link>
      <author>Ruthe Stein</author>
    </item>
    <item index="6">
      <text>It's neither uninteresting nor unentertaining, but the plot is as threadbare as an old carpet and Mamet's narrative contortions will leave many viewers scratching their heads.</text>
      <source>ReelViews</source>
      <image>rottentomatoes://image.review.rotten</image>
      <link>http://www.reelviews.net/php_review_template.php?identifier=771</link>
      <author>James Berardinelli</author>
    </item>
    <item index="7">
      <text>Redbelt ranks as one of Mamet's lesser efforts as writer and director.</text>
      <source>Minneapolis Star Tribune</source>
      <image>rottentomatoes://image.review.rotten</image>
      <link>http://www.startribune.com/entertainment/movies/18769279.html</link>
      <author>Colin Covert</author>
    </item>
    <item index="8">
      <text>Incompetently made and covered in corn, this is a martial arts movie that makes you yearn for The Karate Kid. Yes, that movie was corny, as well, but at least it was fun. Redbelt isn't fun, just laughable.</text>
      <source>Detroit News</source>
      <image>rottentomatoes://image.review.rotten</image>
      <link>http://www.detnews.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20080509/ENT02/805090410/1034/ENT02</link>
      <author>Tom Long</author>
    </item>
    <item index="9">
      <text>So gifted is Mamet as a writer and director that he can fascinate us even when he's pulling rabbits out of an empty hat.</text>
      <source>Chicago Sun-Times</source>
      <image>rottentomatoes://image.review.fresh</image>
      <link>http://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/redbelt-2008</link>
      <author>Roger Ebert</author>
    </item>
    <item index="10">
      <text>A sour little 70s-style David Mamet play about the lies, calculations, and ice-cold politics of Hollywood.</text>
      <source>Chicago Reader</source>
      <image>rottentomatoes://image.review.fresh</image>
      <link>http://www.chicagoreader.com/features/stories/moviereviews/080515/</link>
      <author>J. R. Jones</author>
    </item>
    <item index="11">
      <text>While Redbelt may be a character study in search of a movie, that character feels fresh and real.</text>
      <source>Boston Globe</source>
      <image>rottentomatoes://image.review.fresh</image>
      <link>http://www.boston.com/movies/display?display=movie&amp;id=11499</link>
      <author>Ty Burr</author>
    </item>
    <item index="12">
      <text>Redbelt's ultimate Ultimate Fight moment feels sorely lacking.</text>
      <source>Philadelphia Inquirer</source>
      <image>rottentomatoes://image.review.rotten</image>
      <link>http://www.philly.com/inquirer/columnists/steven_rea/20080509_Tumbling_to_an_implausible_end.html</link>
      <author>Steven Rea</author>
    </item>
    <item index="13">
      <text>Teeters precariously between Mamet's typically noirish realm and the kick-ass commercial galaxy, looking not quite at home in either.</text>
      <source>Globe and Mail</source>
      <image>rottentomatoes://image.review.rotten</image>
      <link>http://www.globeandmail.com/servlet/story/MOVIEREVIEWS.20080509.REDBELT09/MovieStory/Entertainment/Movies</link>
      <author>Rick Groen</author>
    </item>
    <item index="14">
      <text>Before it sort of punches itself out in the final few minutes, it's a surprisingly compelling story about honor and betrayal.</text>
      <source>Arizona Republic</source>
      <image>rottentomatoes://image.review.fresh</image>
      <link>http://www.azcentral.com/ent/movies/articles/2008/05/08/20080508redbelt.html</link>
      <author>Bill Goodykoontz</author>
    </item>
  </reviews>
